data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected True, got False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "expected 3, found N" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Clearer intent, better message |

For the "all active" check, `Assert.IsTrue` with `.All()` is fine since there's no built-in "assert all match predicate." Alternatively, loop with individual assertions for per-item diagnostics.

**Other available collection assertions** (MSTest 3.x+):
- `Assert.Contains(item, collection)` — item exists
- `Assert.DoesNotContain(item, collection)` — item absent
- `Assert.ContainsSingle(collection)` — exactly one element (returns it)
- `Assert.IsEmpty(collection)` — zero elements
